PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE The interplay between HLA-DM and its inhibitor HLA-DO affects MHC class II?restricted antigen presentation, yet the precise mechanism is unclear. This project will study how HLA-DO expression regulates HLA-DM localization and thus its function. Furthermore, the changes in the repertoire of peptides bound to MHC class II will be characterized in relationship to the DO/DM ratio. Understanding the mechanisms that control MHC class II?restricted antigen presentation may allow development of new strategies to maintain or regain tolerance to self proteins.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF GENERAL MEDICAL SCIENCES
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE DNA double-strand break repair (DSBR) pathways are critical for maintaining genome integrity and mediating resistance of cancer cells to many types of cancer treatments, including chemotherapy and ionizing radiation (IR). This proposal will define the mechanisms by which SAMHD1 functions to promote DNA DSBR by homologous recombination and thus provide new insights into how SAMHD1 maintains genome integrity and prevents disease, including cancer. Moreover, given the unique ability of SAMHD1 to regulate cellular dNTP pools and metabolize DNA, SAMHD1 may also function as an important biomarker for discriminating resistance of cancer cells to different types of cancer therapies that induce DNA damage, including chemotherapy and IR.

PHR: 8. PROJECT NARRATIVE  The neocortex is important in perception and cognition, but the number and complexity of interactions between cortical neurons necessitates greater understanding of fundamental principles of neocortical organization at the local circuit level (tens to hundreds of neurons) in order to unravel the mechanisms of high level brain functions. This project will examine the functional and connectivity principles of developmentally related neurons, and how that relationship leads to excitatory neuron integration into the circuit and organization of cortical function. The results of this project will have the potential to reveal fundamental new insights into how the cortex processes incoming information and will thus enable a more principled understanding of normal and abnormal brain function, with broad implications for a wide range of currently intractable neuropsychiatric illnesses such as autism and schizophrenia.

PHR: Project Narrative  Adolescents and young adult women (?young women?) diagnosed with pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) are at increased risk for subsequent sexually transmitted infections (STIs), recurrent PID, and adverse reproductive health outcomes. Little is known about the contextual influences on PID self-care behaviors among young women. Therefore, the purpose of this dissertation research training proposal is to examine the context and processes of PID self-care among young women, with a focus on coping strategies and social support, using the infrastructure of a large ongoing nurse intervention trial designed to improve reproductive health outcomes after a PID diagnosis.

PHR: NARRATIVE Chronic illness morbidity has begun to plateau amongst elderly populations, but is on the rise amongst lower- SES, working-age adults. This trend is reflected in the successes of public health officials in engaging elderly, higher-income populations in evidence-based chronic illness self-management programs, but a simultaneous lack of engagement of younger, lower-SES adults reported in the self-management literature. As rates of chronic illness morbidity and mortality and SES-related health disparities climb amongst this age-group, it is more important than ever to identify communication cues that will effectively engage their interest in participating in self-management program research to study and extend the benefits of enhanced self- management to this vulnerable population.

PHR: Project Narrative  During the menopause transition, many healthy women with no history of cognitive dysfunction experience subjective difficulties with sustained attention, motivation for work, organization and working memory. The proposed project aims to determine 1) whether early life adversity and serotonin system vulnerability contribute to executive system dysfunction among menopausal women and 2) the role of estradiol in protecting against this dysfunction. This project is a necessary step towards the identification of biomarkers for risk of cognitive decline during menopause, which could be used to develop novel therapeutics. !

PHR: Project Narrative Rural heart failure patients are more likely to experience poor health outcomes when compared to urban counterparts; however, the impact of rurality on ventricular assist device (VAD) outcomes in advanced heart failure patients is unknown despite the growing number of VAD patients worldwide. The aims of the proposed study examine the relationship between rurality and VAD outcomes including clinical outcomes (death, adverse events and hospital admissions) and patient-reported health-related quality of life. Ultimately, the goal is to identify disparities imposed by geographic location to improve the overall health of rural VAD patients.

IC_NAME: NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF ALLERGY AND INFECTIOUS DISEASES
PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Trichomonas vaginalis is a protozoan parasite that causes the most common non-viral sexually transmitted infection in the United States and worldwide, but the immune response to the parasite is sorely undercharacterized. Drug resistant strains of Trichomonas vaginalis are increasing, and the parasite is associated with myriad reproductive complications, and increased incidences of HIV infection, cervical cancer, and prostate cancer. The proposed study aims to characterize how Trichomonas vaginalis is cleared by the immune system, and how the immune response to the parasite causes inflammation that may lead to pathology, in order to inform immunotherapy interventions.

PHR: Project Narrative NMDAR antagonists are used to treat Major Depressive Disorder (MDD), although a clear understanding of their mechanism is unknown. PHR: PROJECT NARRATIVE Aerobic exercise is considered to be one of the most effective protective factors that promotes healthy brain aging and attenuates cognitive decline in relation to aging, but the mechanism behind this is not yet well understood. This project addresses the possibility that cardio-respiratory fitness may be a factor that regulates the function of the hippocampal memory system targeted in aging. Importantly, this project investigates the role of fitness across adulthood in hopes of providing evidence for targeted implementation of aerobic exercise interventions at crucial points throughout the lifespan.

IC_NAME: EUNICE KENNEDY SHRIVER NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF CHILD HEALTH & HUMAN DEVELOPMENT
PHR: PUBLIC HEALTH RELEVANCE: Iron deficiency affects approximately 2 billion people worldwide and causes significant neurobehavioral abnormalities in children (e.g. learning and memory deficits). These persist into adulthood despite iron repletion, thus constituting the real cost to society in terms of education and job potential loss. An understanding of the responsible cellular mechanisms is necessary in order to develop more effective therapies that prevent the long-lasting effects. This proposal tests the hypothesis that reduced neuronal energy status and mitochondrial function early in life forms the mechanistic basis for the blunted neuronal maturation observed in the hippocampus following iron deficiency during development.

PHR: PUBLIC HEALTH RELEVANCE: Bacteriophages mediate horizontal gene transfer (HGT), the exchange of novel genetic materials between bacteria, transforming otherwise benign bacteria into human pathogens and driving the rapid emergence of pathogens resistant to existing treatments. Accordingly, there is a critical need to elucidate when, where, and how phage-mediated HGT occurs. Our proposal focuses on using novel technologies to answer these questions for bacteriophage lambda and its host, E. coli.

PHR: PUBLIC HEALTH RELEVANCE: Cognitive decline occurs in women during menopause following the loss of the neuroprotective effects of estrogen and is associated with the etiology of Alzheimer's disease, but there are no therapeutics currently recommended or being evaluated in clinical trials to prevent this cognitive decline. With an aging female population, ths lack of therapeutics comes at a tremendous socioeconomic cost, and treatments that could delay or prevent the onset of cognitive decline during menopause remain an unmet, yet pressing clinical need. We propose a novel strategy to prevent cognitive decline in a preclinical menopause model through estrogen receptor ? (ER?)-mediated neuroprotection, which would be safe and effective for translational dosing in human clinical trials, and we aim to determine the cellular mediator of estrogen's neuroprotective effects in the hippocampus and to characterize the estrogen-sensitive transcriptome in the hippocampal neurons, to ultimately advance our understanding of how estrogens promote hippocampal synaptic plasticity and function to improve the cognitive health of menopausal women worldwide.

PHR: PROJECT RELEVANCE Exposure to stressful environments in early childhood can cause a toxic stress response, and subsequently lead to poor health outcomes including obesity, cardiac disease, diabetes and mental illness.
